'''''Superman''''' is a [[video game]] programmed by [[John Dunn (software developer)|John Dunn]] for the Atari Video Computer System (later renamed [[Atari 2600]])<ref>{{cite video game |title=Atari 50 |developer=[[Digital Eclipse]] |publisher=[[Atari SA|Atari]] |date=November 11, 2022 |platform=Nintendo Switch |quote='''1982: Atari 2600''': With the impending release of its next-generation platform Atari 5200, Atari rebranded the VCS to the Atari 2600.}}</ref> and released in 1979 by [[Atari, Inc.]] The player controls [[Superman]], whose quest is to explore an open-ended environment to find three pieces of a bridge that was destroyed by [[Lex Luthor]], capture Luthor and his criminal gang, and return to the [[Daily Planet]] building. The game world is populated by antagonists such as a helicopter that re-arranges the bridge pieces and roving [[kryptonite]] satellites that cause Superman to revert into Clark Kent.

Atari was owned by [[WarnerMedia|Warner Communications]], which was also the parent company of Superman publisher [[DC Comics]]. Following the financial success of the film ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]'' (1978), Atari asked programmer [[Warren Robinett]] to adapt his prototype of ''[[Adventure (1980 video game)|Adventure]]'' (1980) into a Superman game. Robinett was not interested, but he gave some of his code to Dunn, who agreed to do the game if he could have four [[kilobytes]] of space for the cartridge, as opposed to the usual two kilobytes.

''Superman'' received positive reviews on its release from the publications ''[[Video (magazine)|Video]]'' and ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' who proclaimed it as one of the best games from Atari while noting its high quality graphics and unique gameplay. Some retrospective reviews lamented that the game only used the character of Superman for his more action-oriented abilities, while others continued to praise the game's unique gameplay and high-quality Atari 2600 graphics.

==Gameplay==
[[Image:Superman Atari 2600 screenshot1a.png|thumb|left|alt=Pixel graphic image that represents a grey city skyline. A blue and red stick figure flies over the city.|Superman (center) flying over the city. The bars at the top represent the map of the city block and the right top represents the game's timer.]]
''Superman'' is a video game in which the player controls Clark Kent and his superhero alias [[Superman]].{{sfn|Atari|p=1|1979|ref=manual}} On hearing about a bomb scare in [[Metropolis (comics)|Metropolis]], Kent examines the situation and finds Superman's nemesis [[Lex Luthor]] leaving the scene as the waterfront bridge explodes. The goal is to repair the bridge, which has split into three parts, capture Luthor, and return to the [[Daily Planet]] as Kent in the shortest time possible.{{sfn|Atari|p=2|1979|ref=manual}}{{sfn|Miller}} Superman can be damaged by [[kryptonite]] satellites; if they touch him, he loses his ability to fly and can only be revived by interacting with [[Lois Lane]]. A helicopter moves around Metropolis occasionally moving parts of the bridge around the map.{{sfn|Atari|p=2|1979|ref=manual}} To capture a crook or carry bridge pieces, the player must fly into them to grab them and release them by landing. Luthor and his henchmen are placed in jail by flying them into the jail bars while carrying them.{{sfn|Atari|p=6|1979|ref=manual}} 

The game was made prior to the introduction of [[Side-scrolling video game|side-scrolling]], leading to the player [[flip screen|moving from screen to screen]] and arriving on the next frame for them to enter a new block of Metropolis.{{sfn|Kent|2021|p=497}}{{sfn|Atari|p=3|1979|ref=manual}} A miniature radar consisting of six markers representing city blocks is displayed at the top of the playfield, with the largest marker showing the proximity the player is to the potential targets of Luthor or one of his henchmen. Each of these areas is connected on four adjoining sides, which can be traversed by flying up, down, left and right through the screens.{{sfn|Atari|p=3|1979|ref=manual}} The player can traverse through different subway entrances for quicker travel. After entering, the player can traverse different exits by moving upward off screen through different colored areas and then exiting by moving off screen left, right or down.{{sfn|Atari|p=4|1979|ref=manual}}

The player can enable Superman's x-ray vision to see any of the four adjoining frames. While viewing these, Superman cannot move but can still be hit by kryptonite satellites.{{sfn|Atari|p=6|1979|ref=manual}}

==Development==
In 1976, [[WarnerMedia|Warner Communications]] acquired Atari for $28 million.{{sfn|Aldred|2012|p=91}} Warner Communications also owned [[DC Comics]], which owned the rights to the [[Superman]] character.{{sfn|Wilson|2021|p=198}} The market for comics was shrinking during this period and for the first time, licensing the characters became more profitable, specifically in comparison to the film rentals for the 1978 film ''[[Superman (1978 film)|Superman]]''.{{sfn|Wilson|2021|p=199}} Warner Communications wanted Atari to follow their financially successful film up with a prompt video game tie-in.{{sfn|Aldred|2012|p=93}} According to Jessica Aldred in the book ''Before the Crash'', ''Superman'' was the first film-licensed game for the Atari VCS, while [[Ian Bogost]] and [[Nick Montfort]] in their book ''[[Racing the Beam]]'' (2009) stated that it was not clear that the game was based on the film.{{sfn|Aldred|2012|p=93}}{{sfn|Montfort|Bogost|2009|p=123}} Carl Wilson wrote in ''The Superhero Multiverse'' that [[Mario Puzo]]'s contract had mandated that his story for the ''Superman'' film was not to be adapted into any other form as well as finding that the brief plot summary of the game did not relate to any specific ''Superman'' comic story running at that period.{{sfn|Wilson|2022|p=52}}

[[File:John Dunn (software developer).jpg|thumb|alt=Photograph of bearded man in a plaid shirt sitting at desktop computer next to a sound mixing device.|[[John Dunn (software developer)|John Dunn]] (pictured in 1986) was the programmer of ''Superman''.]]
While developing the game ''[[Adventure (1980 video game)|Adventure]]'' (1980) in 1978, [[Warren Robinett]] was asked to shelve the game and use its design to create a game based on Superman.{{sfn|Montfort|Bogost|2009|p=62}}{{sfn|Robinett|2006|p=694}} At the time, Robinett had a prototype of the game where the player could move a small square "cursor" from screen to screen picking up colored shapes.{{sfn|Robinett|2006|p=694}} Robinett had passed the job on to [[John Dunn (software developer)|John Dunn]], who shared code to facilitated the game's development.{{sfn|Montfort|Bogost|2009|p=62}} According to the game's cover designer Judy Richter, DC Comics were not very hands on in the development of the game and did not give their input or opinions on the game's development.{{sfn|Lapetino|2016|p=91}}

The game was programmed by Dunn in 1978.{{sfn|Montfort|Bogost|2009|p=123}} Dunn took on the job with the condition that he could develop a game that had a four [[kilobyte]] [[Read-only memory|ROM chip]] on its cartridge. With the exception of ''[[Casino (video game)|Casino]]'' (1978) and ''[[Hangman (video game)|Hangman]]'' (1978), every game made for the Atari VCS had been written within two kilobytes.{{sfn|Wilson|2022|p=51}}

For sound and graphics, the Atari 2600 had its [[Television Interface Adaptor]] (TIA) which authors Montfort and Bogost described as a programming challenge, allowing for only a relatively small number of unique features. The Atari 2600 did not allow for such services such as [[Rendering (computer graphics)|graphic rendering]], forcing programmers to draw the entirety of each frame of the game's display.{{sfn|Montfort|Bogost|2009|p=27-28}} The game features no music and only simple sound effects, such as audio getting louder and quieter as Superman flies higher and lower into the air.{{sfn|Miller}} It was one of the first video game with multicolored [[Sprite (computer graphics)|sprites]] and was among the first console games with a pause feature, following the [[Fairchild Channel F]] system.{{sfn|Miller}}{{sfn|Murnane|2016}}{{sfn|Montfort|Bogost|2009|p=105}}

==Release==
In Atari's ''The Atari Video Computer System Catalog'' from 1979, the game was listed as being available soon.{{sfn|Atari|p=37|1979|ref=catalog}} Betsy Staples wrote in September 1979 in ''Creative Computing'' about playing the game at an Electronic expo, while promotional material in newspapers stated the game as arriving soon on September 13, and then being available in stock on September 28.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/64002393/atari-2600-superman-and-more-coming/|work=[[The Honolulu Advertiser]]|date=September 13, 1979|title=Radio Shack Associate Stores-Hawaii|page=H-10|via=Newspapers.com|access-date=February 21, 2023}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/64004337/atari-2600-superman-now-in-stock-sep/|work=The Honolulu Advertiser|date=September 28, 1979|title=Radio Shack Associate Stores-Hawaii|page=B-2|via=[[Newspapers.com]]|access-date=February 21, 2023}}</ref> A review in ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' also stated the game was released in the third quarter of 1979.{{sfn|Howe|1980|p=29}}

According to Richter, DC gave them a playbook on exactly how Superman should look as the cover art was going to be crucial as that is what people would see on the store shelves.{{sfn|Lapetino|2016|p=91}}

==Reception==
[[Bill Kunkel (journalist)|Bill Kunkel]] and [[Arnie Katz]] reviewed ''Superman'' in ''[[Video (magazine)|Video]]'', and declared it as a game that "ushers in an exciting new era for home arcades [...] put simply, there's no game remotely similar to this one", citing that its place in a Video Arcade Hall of Fame "seems assured".{{sfn|Kunkel|Laney|1980|p=18}} ''Video'' established its [[Arcade Awards]], nicknamed the Arkies, to recognize "outstanding achievements in the field of electronic gaming" and had their 1981 edition acknowledge the year's games. ''Superman'' was listed as their "Game of the Year", with the publication declaring it a single-player masterpiece and "the most important release" of the year.<ref>{{cite magazine |year= 1981 |title=Video Games: The Entertainment Revolution! |magazine= [[Electronic Games]] |publisher= Reese Publishing Company, Inc.|volume= 1|issue= 1|pages=38â€“39}}</ref> Norman Howe commented in ''[[The Space Gamer]]'' that he the found moving the character to the edge of the screen to progress to a new area "unusual".{{sfn|Howe|1980|p=29}} Howe proclaimed that the multiple tasks and quick travel systems made it "a fascinating challenge" with "excellent graphics" and declared it "the best Atari game I have yet seen".{{sfn|Howe|1980|p=29}} Among the weak points, Howe noted that it was possible to lose items near the edge of the frame and that the game had a high cost for a single scenario.{{sfn|Howe|1980|p=29}} Another review from ''Electronic Games'' in its "1983 Software Encyclopedia" issue gave it a nine out of ten rating, declaring the gameplay, graphics and sound as "excellent" and stating it was "outstanding" as a single-player game.<ref>{{cite magazine|magazine=[[Electronic Games|Electronic Games 1983 Software Encyclopedia]]|title=Atari 2600 (VCS)|issn=0736-8488|publisher=Reese Communications|year=1983|volume=1|issue=1|page=32}}</ref> The editors and writers of the magazine ''Video and Computer Gaming Illustrated'' listed ''Superman'' as second place for the Best Game not based on an arcade game in March 1984.{{sfn|Video and Computer Gaming Illustrated|1984|p=25|ref=VaCGI}} The publication wrote that "despite what were roundly acknowledged as "wanting" graphics. Several votes remarked that the game has "charm"", specifically noting the many cityscapes in the game and the multiple ways to traverse the map. {{sfn|Video and Computer Gaming Illustrated|1984|pp=33-34|ref=VaCGI}}

Retrospectively, Bogost and Monfort found that ''Superman'' "expunged the movie's social and emotional relationships - and those of the comic books - choosing action sequences instead. Games licensed from movies have continued to follow this early VCS game in this regard".{{sfn|Montfort|Bogost|2009|p=63}} William Wilson of ''Forbes'' stated in 2015 that ''Superman'' was exceptional by contemporary technical standards, noting its graphics being better than some of the competition, specifically comparing it to Atari's ''Adventure''.{{sfn|Wilson|2016}} Skyler Miller of [[AllGame]] gave the game a five out of five star rating, praising the game's re-playability, graphics, but found it not up to the standards of the games developed for the system by [[Activision]]. He also appreciated the smaller details such as the sound of flying decreasing in volume as Superman ascends and Lois Lane lifting her leg when Superman kisses her.{{sfn|Miller}} In 2009, Michal Mozejko of ''[[Retro Gamer]]'' opined that the game was still the best ''Superman'' video game, praising its innovation with being the first to utilize multiple screens as a playing area, although he noted that travelling through the map was not intuitive.{{sfn|Mozejko|2009}}

Superman was the first published superhero to feature in a video game, followed up on the Atari 2600 by ''[[Spider-Man (1982 video game)|Spider-Man]]'' (1982).{{sfn|Kent|2021|p=497}} Following the [[video game crash of 1983]], Warner Communications was without any video game subsidiary as they had divided and sold Atari. Once the video game market began to recover, Warner Communications began licensing out their DC Comics properties to third-party developers.{{sfn|Wilson|2021|p=199}} The next game featuring Superman would appear in 1985: ''[[Superman: The Game]]'' by [[First Star Software]] for the [[Commodore 64]].{{sfn|Darowski|2021|p=257}}

